<div><strong>How to work out the perfect â€œknee-lengthâ€ for you...</strong></div>
</div>
<div class="field-item">
<div class="field-item-image"><a class="imagefield imagefield-lightbox2 imagefield-lightbox2-Gallery imagefield-field_galleryimages imagecache imagecache-field_galleryimages imagecache-Gallery imagecache-field_galleryimages-Gallery lightbox-processed" style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; color: #90416a; text-decoration: none;" href="http://www.sosensational.co.uk/sites/default/files/iStock_000004711388XSmall_1.jpg" rel="lightbox[field_galleryimages][Stand in front of a long mirror wearing tights (or bare legs) and a top. Take a long piece of fabric (or a towel, if you donâ€™t have fabric) and hold it in front of you like an ankle-length skirt, keeping one end firmly at your waist. As you gradually roll the fabric up, you will see which length is the most flattering for your legs â€“ just on, just above or just below the knee. If you can get a friend to help, they should measure the length from waist to â€œhemâ€; that is your best skirt length. If you wear skirts longer, as a general rule, a hem that hits the widest part of the calf will be the least flattering. Either go longer â€“ midi and maxi are both big trends this season â€“ or wear â€œyourâ€ best knee length, which has become a style classic.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.sosensational.co.uk/sites/default/files/iStock_000004711388XSmall_1.jpg&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; id=&quot;lightbox2-download-link-text&quot;&gt;Download Original&lt;/a&gt;]"><img class=" alignleft" title="How to work out the perfect â€œknee-lengthâ€ for you..." src="http://www.sosensational.co.uk/sites/default/files/imagecache/Gallery/iStock_000004711388XSmall_1.jpg" alt="How to work out the perfect â€œknee-lengthâ€ for you..." width="109" height="145" /></a></div>
<div class="field-item-other">
<div class="field-item-other-title">Stand in front of a long mirror wearing tights (or bare legs) and a top. Take a long piece of fabric (or a towel, if you donâ€™t have fabric) and hold it in front of you like an ankle-length skirt, keeping one end firmly at your waist. As you gradually roll the fabric up, you will see which length is the most flattering for your legs â€“ just on, just above or just below the knee. If you can get a friend to help, they should measure the length from waist to â€œhemâ€; that is your best skirt length. If you wear skirts longer, as a general rule, a hem that hits the widest part of the calf will be the least flattering. Either go longer â€“ midi and maxi are both big trends this season â€“ or wear â€œyourâ€ best knee length, which has become a style classic.</div>
</div>
